<br>
I'm pretty sure that you are referring to the Scopes Monkey Trial. There's a good movie based on it, with some fair accurracy to it. I believe Jason Robards plays one of the lawyers, perhaps even Darrow.<br>
<br>
Fkin wrote, &quot;Sorry, but the only 'forcing' going on is the people (presumably like yourself) that want to mandate christian practices on others. Nobody is stopping you from chanting whatever quasi religious mumbo jumbo you want - it is the espousing of a single religion (in this case christianity) that is going on - this has been pointed out numerous times.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, this is one man forcing his religious non-beliefs on the rest of the country. His belief pseudo-system mandates that there is no God, no Godhead, no higher powers, etc. Okay, fine, no sweat from me. However, the modern version of Atheism, non-philosophy that it is, mandates additionally that no one should force anyone to refer to any higher power, God, Godhead, etc. <br>
<br>
If it doesn't exist, as Atheists are so certain, what is the harm in talking to it?<br>
<br>
Additionally, it is more than a bit narrow-minded to assume that the &quot;under God&quot; line is espousing Christianity. Here's a clue, all monotheistic cultures call their god &quot;God&quot;, in some way. &quot;Allah&quot; is &quot;God&quot;. &quot;Yahweh&quot; is &quot;God&quot;.  Go down the line and you'll see that &quot;God&quot; is pretty much the English word for &quot;God&quot;. Simple, eh?<br>
<br>
It is still arguable though that the &quot;under God&quot; line does, in fact, espouse Monotheism. Could argue that. I would still advise one to examine many Dualist and Polytheistic faiths. You'd find, frequently, a central/important figured named, in the local parlance, &quot;God&quot;. Now, you could argue that an Animist wouldn't call anything &quot;god&quot; or that a Pantheist wouldn't be so exclusionary as to call any single entity &quot;God&quot;, but then we'd grasping at straws. <br>
<br>
