Actually, Hindus are essentially monotheists. The various gods of the Hindu pantheon are but masks on the face of Brahmin. Brahmin (or Brahmen, or any number of incorrect Western transliterations) is the light and source of all things and pervades all. Brahmin is the only God, as it were, and others are merely aspects. If you'd like to debate Hinduism at length, I am happy to.<br>
<br>
Buddhism is not particularly a religion at all, do your homework. It is a belief system that has no godhead to worship. In Buddhism, one reveres the Buddha, but does not worship him. One aspires to be like the Buddha, but does not abase onesself to the Buddha. <br>
<br>
Depending on the brand of Buddhism you are referring to, the primary aspiration is to either divest  one's self of consciousness (usually Chan or Zen Buddhism), or to subsume one's self into the mass consciousness of reality. In neither case does a god of any sort enter into the equation as there is no worship, per se.<br>
<br>
Without a Godhead, it is difficult to conceive of Buddhism as a religion. Still, this would mean that it should be included as an atheism, in essence. <br>
<br>
Now, check an atlas. Examine which areas corresponde to which faiths. The major monotheistic faiths are Islam (of all stripes -Sunni, Shi'a, Sufi, etc.),  Christianity (Catholicism, protestantism, Greek Ortho, Russian Ortho, etc), Judaism, and Hinduism. The only heavily populated areas that do not hold one of these faiths as dominant would be the lower Asian sector, primarily China, Japan, and Korea. In each case, you have a serious minority that is monotheistic in some way, usually Muslim or Christian. The ones that are not fall under pantheists and atheists, true, but India, Northern Asia (Russia, etc), Europe, and North and South America taken together have easily enough people to out-populate the portion of Asia that is not monotheistic. In point of fact, the fastest growing religion on the planet is Islam. It has reached parity with the Chinese in population by itself.<br>
<br>
Am I saying that Monotheism is completely dominant? No. It does however have a plurality and a majority.<br>
<br>
